  <!-- ── Post Body ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <article class="post-body">

    <p>I wanted a look that felt confident and modern. Not soft natural light. Not flat studio light. The focus was on strong shape, controlled shadows, and a touch of color to add depth — the kind of lighting often seen in fashion and editorial work, and increasingly in personal branding photography for creators, founders, and professionals who want portraits that actually stand out.</p>

    <div class="post-pullquote">
      <p>Good portraits are about how light is used, not how much light is used. With the right approach, even a simple setup creates strong results.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>How I Approached the Lighting</h2>
    <p>I kept the setup deliberately minimal. One main light shaped the face, and small accent lights added separation and color depth. Instead of removing shadows — which is the instinct in most portrait work — I let them stay. But in a clean, flattering, controlled way.</p>
    <p>This approach consistently produces:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Strong, defined facial structure that reads clearly on screen and in print</li>
      <li>A bold, editorial quality that separates the image from typical headshots</li>
      <li>Consistent, repeatable results even in relatively short sessions</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Image Placeholder — mid post -->
    <div class="post-img">
      <div class="post-img-placeholder">
        <svg class="img-icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><rect x="3" y="3" width="18" height="18" rx="2"/><circle cx="8.5" cy="8.5" r="1.5"/><polyline points="21 15 16 10 5 21"/></svg>
        <span>Add lighting detail photo → assets/images/blog-editorial-2.webp</span>
      </div>
      <p class="post-img-caption">The setup — one key light, accent separation, controlled shadow</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Why This Style Works for Personal Branding</h2>
    <p>Editorial lighting makes a portrait stand out because it feels intentional. It communicates confidence, polish, and creative awareness — qualities that matter if you're a creator, an influencer, a founder, or any professional building a public presence online.</p>
    <p>Standard headshots are lit to be safe. Editorial portraits are lit to make an impression. For LinkedIn profiles, website hero images, speaker bios, and press features, there's a meaningful difference between the two.</p>
    <p>This style works particularly well for:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Creators and content producers building a recognisable personal brand</li>
      <li>Founders and executives who want imagery that reflects leadership</li>
      <li>Personal branding sessions for professionals in Houston and Katy TX</li>
      <li>Editorial or fashion-inspired portrait work</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The Lesson</h2>
    <p>This study reminded me that the most interesting photography decisions are usually about restraint, not addition. One carefully positioned light does more than three lights placed without thought. A shadow that falls in the right place adds dimension. A color accent that's barely visible in the setup creates depth you feel more than see.</p>
    <p>Every session I do — whether it's a corporate event in Houston, a family portrait in Katy, or a personal branding shoot — is informed by this kind of deliberate thinking about light. That's what I mean when I say every image is made with intention.</p>

